text: DOSS, DESMOND T. Rank and organization: Private First Class, U.S. Army, Medical Detachment, 307th Infantry, 77th Infantry Division Place and date: Near Urasoe Mura, Okinawa, Ryukyu Islands, 29 April-21 May 1945 Entered service at: Lynchburg, Va. G.O. No.: 97, 1 November 1945 Citation: He was a company aid man when the 1st Battalion assaulted a jagged escarpment 400 feet high As our troops gained the summit, a heavy concentration of artillery, mortar and machinegun fire crashed into them, inflicting approximately 75 casualties and driving the others back. Pfc. Doss refused to seek cover and remained in the fire-swept area with the many stricken, carrying them 1 by 1 to the edge of the escarpment and there lowering them on a rope-supported litter down the face of a cliff to friendly hands. On 2 May, he exposed himself to heavy rifle and mortar fire in rescuing a wounded man 200 yards forward of the lines on the same escarpment; and 2 days later he treated 4 men who had been cut down while assaulting a strongly defended cave, advancing through a shower of grenades to within 8 yards of enemy forces in a cave's mouth, where he dressed his comrades' wounds before making 4 separate trips under fire to evacuate them to safety. On 5 May, he unhesitatingly braved enemy shelling and small arms fire to assist an artillery officer. He applied bandages, moved his patient to a spot that offered protection from small arms fire and, while artillery and mortar shells fell close by, painstakingly administered plasma. Later that day, when an American was severely wounded by fire from a cave, Pfc. Doss crawled to him where he had fallen 25 feet from the enemy position, rendered aid, and carried him 100 yards to safety while continually exposed to enemy fire. On 21 May, in a night attack on high ground near Shuri, he remained in exposed territory while the rest of his company took cover, fearlessly risking the chance that he would be mistaken for an infiltrating Japanese and giving aid to the injured until he was himself seriously wounded in the legs by the explosion of a grenade. Rather than call another aid man from cover, he cared for his own injuries and waited 5 hours before litter bearers reached him and started carrying him to cover. The trio was caught in an enemy tank attack and Pfc. Doss, seeing a more critically wounded man nearby, crawled off the litter; and directed the bearers to give their first attention to the other man. Awaiting the litter bearers' return, he was again struck, this time suffering a compound fracture of 1 arm. With magnificent fortitude he bound a rifle stock to his shattered arm as a splint and then crawled 300 yards over rough terrain to the aid station. Through his outstanding bravery and unflinching determination in the face of desperately dangerous conditions Pfc. Doss saved the lives of many soldiers. His name became a symbol throughout the 77th Infantry Division for outstanding gallantry far above and beyond the call of duty.

If the worldÂ had a few more people like the one depicted in the movie, whoÂ follows his religious beliefs rather than twist them to justify what they are doing,Â then we all wouldn't be having to look over our shoulders waiting for the next suicide bomber to explode.

text: The official Citation for the Medal of Honor for PFC Desmond Doss:  Rank and organization: Private First Class, United States Army, Medical Detachment, 307th Infantry, 77th Infantry Division.   Place and date: Near Urasoe Mura, Okinawa, Ryukyu Islands, April 29, 1945 â€“ May 21, 1945.   Entered service at: Lynchburg, Virginia   Birth: Lynchburg, Virginia   G.O. No.: 97, November 1, 1945.   Citation:   He was a company aid man when the 1st Battalion assaulted a jagged escarpment 400 feet high. As our troops gained the summit, a heavy concentration of artillery, mortar and machinegun fire crashed into them, inflicting approximately 75 casualties and driving the others back. Pfc. Doss refused to seek cover and remained in the fire-swept area with the many stricken, carrying all 75 casualties one-by-one to the edge of the escarpment and there lowering them on a rope-supported litter down the face of a cliff to friendly hands. On May 2, he exposed himself to heavy rifle and mortar fire in rescuing a wounded man 200 yards forward of the lines on the same escarpment; and 2 days later he treated 4 men who had been cut down while assaulting a strongly defended cave, advancing through a shower of grenades to within 8 yards of enemy forces in a cave's mouth, where he dressed his comrades' wounds before making 4 separate trips under fire to evacuate them to safety. On May 5, he unhesitatingly braved enemy shelling and small arms fire to assist an artillery officer. He applied bandages, moved his patient to a spot that offered protection from small arms fire and, while artillery and mortar shells fell close by, painstakingly administered plasma. Later that day, when an American was severely wounded by fire from a cave, Pfc. Doss crawled to him where he had fallen 25 feet from the enemy position, rendered aid, and carried him 100 yards to safety while continually exposed to enemy fire. On May 21, in a night attack on high ground near Shuri, he remained in exposed territory while the rest of his company took cover, fearlessly risking the chance that he would be mistaken for an infiltrating Japanese and giving aid to the injured until he was himself seriously wounded in the legs by the explosion of a grenade. Rather than call another aid man from cover, he cared for his own injuries and waited 5 hours before litter bearers reached him and started carrying him to cover. The trio was caught in an enemy tank attack and Pfc. Doss, seeing a more critically wounded man nearby, crawled off the litter; and directed the bearers to give their first attention to the other man. Awaiting the litter bearers' return, he was again struck, by a sniper bullet while being carried off the field by a comrade, this time suffering a compound fracture of 1 arm. With magnificent fortitude he bound a rifle stock to his shattered arm as a splint and then crawled 300 yards over rough terrain to the aid station. Through his outstanding bravery and unflinching determination in the face of desperately dangerous conditions Pfc. Doss saved the lives of many soldiers. His name became a symbol throughout the 77th Infantry Division for outstanding gallantry far above and beyond the call of duty.

text: This is Private Doss Citation for his Medal Of Honor: He was a company aid man when the 1st Battalion assaulted a jagged escarpment 400 feet high As our troops gained the summit, a heavy concentration of artillery, mortar and machinegun fire crashed into them, inflicting approximately 75 casualties and driving the others back. Pfc. Doss refused to seek cover and remained in the fire-swept area with the many stricken, carrying them 1 by 1 to the edge of the escarpment and there lowering them on a rope-supported litter down the face of a cliff to friendly hands. On 2 May, he exposed himself to heavy rifle and mortar fire in rescuing a wounded man 200 yards forward of the lines on the same escarpment; and 2 days later he treated 4 men who had been cut down while assaulting a strongly defended cave, advancing through a shower of grenades to within 8 yards of enemy forces in a cave's mouth, where he dressed his comrades' wounds before making 4 separate trips under fire to evacuate them to safety. On 5 May, he unhesitatingly braved enemy shelling and small arms fire to assist an artillery officer. He applied bandages, moved his patient to a spot that offered protection from small arms fire and, while artillery and mortar shells fell close by, painstakingly administered plasma. Later that day, when an American was severely wounded by fire from a cave, Pfc. Doss crawled to him where he had fallen 25 feet from the enemy position, rendered aid, and carried him 100 yards to safety while continually exposed to enemy fire. On 21 May, in a night attack on high ground near Shuri, he remained in exposed territory while the rest of his company took cover, fearlessly risking the chance that he would be mistaken for an infiltrating Japanese and giving aid to the injured until he was himself seriously wounded in the legs by the explosion of a grenade. Rather than call another aid man from cover, he cared for his own injuries and waited 5 hours before litter bearers reached him and started carrying him to cover. The trio was caught in an enemy tank attack and Pfc. Doss, seeing a more critically wounded man nearby, crawled off the litter; and directed the bearers to give their first attention to the other man. Awaiting the litter bearers' return, he was again struck, this time suffering a compound fracture of 1 arm. With magnificent fortitude he bound a rifle stock to his shattered arm as a splint and then crawled 300 yards over rough terrain to the aid station. Through his outstanding bravery and unflinching determination in the face of desperately dangerous conditions Pfc. Doss saved the lives of many soldiers. His name became a symbol throughout the 77th Infantry Division for outstanding gallantry far above and beyond the call of duty.

text: When I was a boy i believed heroes were men who killed alot of the enemy. In high school i did a report on men in combat in all the wars. There was a VFW post near me that my uncles belong to and interviewed a lot of combat vets from all branches of the military. One of the questions I asked them was who was the bravest man in their in there outfit and 90 % said it was their medic or corpsman stating , "Any man who goes into combat without a weapon is either crazy or very brave." All witnessed a medic running from cover to give aid to a wounded comrade and  with tears in their eyes told me many were killed doing so. Some even said it turned the tide in battle angering the other men so much that all they wanted to do was kill the " bastards" that shot the medic who was unarmed. This was not from a movie, this was from real combat vets not seeking glory but just wanting to survive the horrors of war. They also said no real soldier wants war only killers do.

text: Desmond Doss was a Seventh Day Adventist and, thanks to his religious beliefs, was classified as a conscientious objector which saved him from the draft.  He refused to pick up a weapon and refused to work on Saturday (Seventh Day Adventists worship on Saturday instead of Sunday because they believe that day is the Sabbath).  Despite all of that he served in the Pacific during World War 2 as a medic, was wounded three times, lost a lung to tuberculosis, and was the first of only three conscientious objectors in American history to be awarded the Congressional Medal of Honor.

text: Below is the citation for why Desmond (character film is based on) received Medal of Honor-medal, read and cry.   He was a company aid man when the 1st Battalion assaulted a jagged escarpment 400 feet high. As our troops gained the summit, a heavy concentration of artillery, mortar and machinegun fire crashed into them, inflicting approximately 75 casualties and driving the others back. Pfc. Doss refused to seek cover and remained in the fire-swept area with the many stricken, carrying all 75 casualties one-by-one to the edge of the escarpment and there lowering them on a rope-supported litter down the face of a cliff to friendly hands. On May 2, he exposed himself to heavy rifle and mortar fire in rescuing a wounded man 200 yards forward of the lines on the same escarpment; and 2 days later he treated 4 men who had been cut down while assaulting a strongly defended cave, advancing through a shower of grenades to within eight yards of enemy forces in a cave's mouth, where he dressed his comrades' wounds before making 4 separate trips under fire to evacuate them to safety. On May 5, he unhesitatingly braved enemy shelling and small arms fire to assist an artillery officer. He applied bandages, moved his patient to a spot that offered protection from small arms fire and, while artillery and mortar shells fell close by, painstakingly administered plasma. Later that day, when an American was severely wounded by fire from a cave, Pfc. Doss crawled to him where he had fallen 25 feet from the enemy position, rendered aid, and carried him 100 yards to safety while continually exposed to enemy fire. On May 21, in a night attack on high ground near Shuri, he remained in exposed territory while the rest of his company took cover, fearlessly risking the chance that he would be mistaken for an infiltrating Japanese and giving aid to the injured until he was himself seriously wounded in the legs by the explosion of a grenade. Rather than call another aid man from cover, he cared for his own injuries and waited 5 hours before litter bearers reached him and started carrying him to cover. The trio was caught in an enemy tank attack and Pfc. Doss, seeing a more critically wounded man nearby, crawled off the litter; and directed the bearers to give their first attention to the other man. Awaiting the litter bearers' return, he was again struck, by a sniper bullet while being carried off the field by a comrade, this time suffering a compound fracture of 1 arm. With magnificent fortitude he bound a rifle stock to his shattered arm as a splint and then crawled 300 yards over rough terrain to the aid station. Through his outstanding bravery and unflinching determination in the face of desperately dangerous conditions Pfc. Doss saved the lives of many soldiers. His name became a symbol throughout the 77th Infantry Division for outstanding gallantry far above and beyond the call of duty.

text: This is actually based on a real story about a Seventh Day Adventist who was a pacifist. He got the Congressional Medal of Honor for bravery because he carried more than 30 wounded men from the battlefield, under fire. Now why they didn't just make him a medic in the first place is beyond me. The guy did an amazing job. I saw an interview with him and he said he visited the place where a battle had been--this was 20 years later. A bunch of Japanese tourists were there, too. He was so glad that he could honestly tell them that he didn't hurt any of their people.Â  Incredible guy. My hat is off.

text: True story about Desmond Doss, a Seventh Day Adventist conscientious objector, who was awarded the Medal of Honor for singlehandedly saving at least 75 men on the battlefield in Okinawa ,Japan in one day. He saved many more than that on the Maeda Escarpment before that one fateful day. Before this, he was almost court-martialed because he did not want to carry a weapon into battle. He was very familiar with guns and had handled them many times growing up, firing at targets only. He only had an 8th grade education. In 2004, a documentary by Terry Benedict titled "The Conscientious Objector" won many awards and was shown many times around the world, even on The Armed Forces Network & The Pentagon Channel. This  eventually led to Fox Studios earning the rights to make the movie " Hacksaw Ridge". They had to convince the Desmond Doss Council that Doss's story would be protected, preserved and it would capture the essence of Desmond's service.

text: He was a company aid man when the 1st Battalion assaulted a jaggedÂ escarpmentÂ 400 feet high. As our troops gained the summit, a heavy concentration ofartillery,Â mortarÂ andmachine gunÂ fire crashed into them, inflicting approximately 75 casualties and driving the others back. Pfc. Doss refused to seek cover and remained in the fire-swept area with the many stricken, carrying all 75 casualties one-by-one to the edge of the escarpment and there lowering them on a rope-supported litter down the face of a cliff to friendly hands. On May 2, he exposed himself to heavy rifle and mortar fire in rescuing a wounded man 200 yards forward of the lines on the same escarpment; and 2 days later he treated 4 men who had been cut down while assaulting a strongly defended cave, advancing through a shower ofÂ grenadesÂ to within eight yards of enemy forces in a cave's mouth, where he dressed his comrades' wounds before making 4 separate trips under fire to evacuate them to safety. On May 5, he unhesitatingly braved enemy shelling and small arms fire to assist an artillery officer. He applied bandages, moved his patient to a spot that offered protection from small arms fire and, while artillery and mortar shells fell close by, painstakingly administeredÂ plasma. Later that day, when an American was severely wounded by fire from a cave, Pfc. Doss crawled to him where he had fallen 25 feet from the enemy position, rendered aid, and carried him 100 yards to safety while continually exposed to enemy fire. On May 21, in a night attack on high ground near Shuri, he remained in exposed territory while the rest of his company took cover, fearlessly risking the chance that he would be mistaken for an infiltrating Japanese and giving aid to the injured until he was himself seriously wounded in the legs by the explosion of a grenade. Rather than call another aid man from cover, he cared for his own injuries and waited 5 hours beforeÂ litterbearers reached him and started carrying him to cover. The trio was caught in an enemytankÂ attack and Pfc. Doss, seeing a more critically wounded man nearby, crawled off the litter; and directed the bearers to give their first attention to the other man. Awaiting the litter bearers' return, he was again struck, by a sniper bullet while being carried off the field by a comrade, this time suffering aÂ compound fractureÂ of one arm. With magnificent fortitude he bound a rifle stock to his shattered arm as aÂ splintand then crawled 300 yards over rough terrain to the aid station. Through his outstanding bravery and unflinching determination in the face of desperately dangerous conditions Pfc. Doss saved the lives of many soldiers. His name became a symbol throughout the 77th Infantry Division for outstanding gallantry far above and beyond the call of duty.

text: *PRIVATE DOSS - THOU SHALT NOT KILL??* Like Doss I too am a Seventh Day Adventist (I keep the Sabbath and believe in keeping ALL the 10 Commandments - not for my salvation as I am saved by grace but as a true demonstration of the love I have for God.) *  1John 5:3 "For this is the love of God, that we keep his commandments:"  BUT I have to say,  although I have the greatest admiration for Desmond Doss his belief in  pacifism is not a biblical one. Before I go further I should say neither is it a sin to be a pacifist.  There are numerous examples in Scripture where men of God were forced to defend themselves from the enemy who were trying to kill them. Doss' interpretation of the command - "thou shalt not kill" Exodus 20.13 is erroneous. the word "KILL" used in the King James is better translated, "thou shalt not murder" - a BIG difference. Strongs Concordance word No. (H7523).   Never the less, Doss's demonstration of love to his fellow man is a wonderful example of Christian charity and love for his fellow man and reveals a depth of character I and many people would wish to emulate.

text: A powerful film -- all the more so for it being based on the life of a real individual, which again proves the fact that truth can be stranger than fiction.  However, I cannot recommend the film to everyone.  For instance, I had to watch the film alone, knowing that my wife would be revolted by the scenes of carnage.  The graphic depictions of violence in war do not require an excuse, but some people ought to be warned that such scenes are very realistic and repellant.  Should Mel have toned it down to make the picture more palatable to a wider audience?  Hell if I know.  He made the film he wanted to make, and we can either take it or leave it.  It does bring up the question of how much graphic violence is required to make a war film (such as this) believable and thought-worthy.  Sometimes the mere suggestion of a thing can be as effective as its actual depiction -- maybe more so.  Again, something to ponder.
